The access matrix approach can become unwieldy when stored directly because it scales poorly with the number of subjects (processes) and objects (resources), leading to a large, sparse matrix that is difficult to manage efficiently. While other options may have some relevance, the primary challenge is the **size and complexity of the matrix itself** when implemented naively. This issue has historically driven the development of alternatives like access control lists (ACLs) or capability lists.
